Heil wants to examine other industries after meat industry
The Corona crisis brought the conditions in parts of the meat industry back to light.
Tightening of the law is imminent.
But are they right - and will it stay that way?
Federal Minister of Labour Hubertus Heil (SPD) wants to review other sectors after the now planned strict regulations against grievances in the meat industry.
"We will look at industry by industry and then take appropriate measures for the respective industry if necessary," Heil told the German Press Agency in Berlin.
Germany's employers are already warning against restricting work contracts in general.
After the mass Corona outbreak at the meat giant Tönnies in North Rhine-Westphalia, the Federal Cabinet wants to pass a law of salvation this Wednesday.
Large slaughterhouses should no longer be allowed to use external personnel for slaughter, dismantling and meat processing.
For this purpose, the use of contract and temporary workers is to be prohibited there.
Employer president Ingo Kramer told the dpa: "Hands off a general restriction on work contracts and temporary employment if you do not want to completely stifle the economy".
Work contracts, for example, are the basis for customer value creation for large areas of crafts, the construction industry and plant engineering.
"The misdeeds of individuals cannot destroy such an important instrument".
Heil assured: "My goal is not to ban work contracts everywhere in the German economy".
Work contracts make sense.
"If an industrial company commissions a craftsman to install a safety system, that is a normal work contract".
The German meat industry considers a ban on work contracts and temporary work in its industry alone to be unconstitutional.
It cannot be explained why different labour law should apply to portioning and packaging cheese in the future than to sausage, according to a statement on the proposed law, as reported by the "Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung" (Saturday).
In the event of a ban, the consumer price would rise by 10 to 20 percent per kilo and product.
According to the results of an audit by the NRW Occupational Safety and Health Administration, many Eastern European employees from contract companies sometimes worked 16 hours a day in the industry.
They often had no break.
Wages were withheld for protective equipment or rent.
It was also noted that the situation regarding the accommodation of employees was often miserable.
Heil said that a relatively strict law had already come into force for the meat industry in 2017.
However, these were circumvented by "tricky constructions".
"Now we have to clean up fundamentally".
The politician announced: "The Occupational Safety and Health Act, which we intend to adopt in the cabinet at the end of July, also includes measures that do not only affect the meat industry - for example, higher inspection rates for occupational safety or clear criteria for community accommodation".
The draft submitted to dpa includes amendments to the Act on the Protection of Workers' Rights in the Meat Industry and the Occupational Safety and Health Act.
Brandenburg's Consumer Protection Minister Ursula Nonnemacher (Greens) considers more intensive controls necessary.
"I would like us to be able to carry out even more controls in many supervisory areas: food controls, animal welfare, everything possible, for example animal transport," said Nonnemacher on Sunday in the RBB program "Brandenburg aktuell".
However, more staff positions are also needed for more controls.
