Baden-Württemberg: More than 250 illegal car races recorded
Stuttgart - Despite all threatened penalties and court rulings, drivers continue to step on the gas in countless illegal races on the roads of Baden-Württemberg: Last year and the first four months of this year, the police in the southwest have already registered more than 250 illegal car races.
There are no comparative values for the years before, but the speeders are increasingly making the judicial authorities work: the public prosecutors between Konstanz and Mannheim conducted a total of 155 preliminary investigations for illegal races in 2018, a year later there were already 252 and in the current year until the beginning of June already 151.
The races were less about organized events, as can be seen from the response of the Interior Ministry to a request from the state parliament SPD.
In most cases, the drivers spontaneously competed against each other or fled from the police - this is also reported as an illegal race.
At the wheel were mainly German men between the ages of 18 and 60.
113 Fines - 15 times imprisonment
Only in comparatively few cases are the speeders caught and also asked to pay: according to the Ministry of the Interior, a total of 113 fines have been imposed and 15 prison sentences pronounced since 2018.
However, there is no evidence that the number of illegal car races is actually increasing.
Rather, other drivers reacted more sensitively than before due to the numerous tragic accidents and trials of past years and reported more frequently, said a ministry spokesman.
The Autobahn 8 is particularly popular with speeders. Again and again, drivers brake the traffic there to make room for themselves and use the free track for a race.
Last August, a dozen drivers were caught near Kirchheim unter Teck, three months earlier there were even 18 drivers on the A8 near Merklingen.
A81 is the most popular "race track"
The police even register more races on the A81 than on any other federal motorway.
With a speed limit, attempts are made to slow down the speeders on the particularly affected section between Engen and Geisingen.
The mostly high-priced and pimped-up sports and luxury cars often have Swiss license plates, because the drivers switch to the grass in Germany because of the high penalties for driving too fast and car racing in the neighboring country.
For the SPD, the speed limit must not be reduced to a few distances: "With a general speed limit of 130 kilometers per hour, we would solve this problem on motorways," says Martin Rivoir, the traffic expert of the SPD parliamentary group.
"The inhibition threshold for speeders would be significantly higher if you could not legally travel here and there at 200 kilometers per hour and more".
Rivoir thinks less of education or image campaigns: "Anyone who disregards all rules in such a way and puts not only their own lives, but also the lives of other road users at risk, is hardly reachable with reason".
ADAC calls for stronger police crackdown
For the ADAC, however, this is not enough: "We assume that speeders will not be deterred by the speed limits," says Holger Bach, Head of Transport and Environment at the ADAC Württemberg.
He calls for additional and tougher controls on the affected routes.
It is not uncommon for the high-speed trial of strength to become painful and serious: Since January 2019 and until April 2020, three people across the country have died in the races, two of them uninvolved in a nightly crash in Stuttgart city center and one in Gerlingen.
Two young men are said to have had a car race there in November.
One of the vehicles came off the road, crashed into a garden wall and remained lying on its side, the 18-year-old passenger died.
21 Other people have been injured in the races of the past two years.
However, according to Interior Minister Thomas Strobl, stricter penalties are not necessary: "There is no need for legislative action to sanction illegal motor vehicle races more severely," says the Interior Ministry's paper.
