Austria: Mass tests after Corona outbreak in tourist resort
Authorities have responded to a Corona outbreak in the popular Upper Austrian tourist resort of St. Wolfgang with hundreds of tests.
The number of confirmed cases rose to 48, according to the state authorities in Linz.
More than 100 results were still pending in the evening.
Accordingly, many of those infected are young interns in tourism businesses, but at least one holiday guest tested positive.
Residents, guests and tourism staff were asked to stay in their accommodation on Saturday evening.
The curfew was set at 11 p.m.
"There are cancellations and cancellations there and there" of bookings, Hans Wieser, head of the Wolfgangsee Tourism Association, told dpa.
Some guests also left early.
St. Wolfgang is the most important tourist resort in Upper Austria, with more than 400,000 overnight stays last year.
In a normal season, around one third of the guests are German.
The first infections became public knowledge on Friday.
On Saturday, the head of the district authority, Alois Lanz, defended the behaviour of the interns, who had celebrated in several restaurants and may have been infected there.
"We all enjoyed doing that in our youth," he told the radio station Ö1.
However, two bars were closed on Friday to prevent further infections.
The tourism association launched an information campaign to sensitize young employees to the dangers of Covid-19.
Starting on Saturday, hundreds of employees, holidaymakers and locals were tested.
In addition, all guests who were in St. Wolfgang from July 15 were contacted.
The outbreak evokes memories of the Austrian ski and party resort of Ischgl in Tyrol, which was a center of the Corona spread throughout Europe in the early phase of the pandemic.
Altogether, more than 1500 people in Austria are currently infected with the virus.
The new infections focus on Vienna and Upper Austria.
