Fleetwood Mac co-founder Peter Green died
His life was like a rollercoaster ride: after a rapid ascent with Fleetwood Mac, it went steeply downhill and then slowly up again.
Blues rock guitarist Peter Green has now died at the age of 73.
Ingenious guitarist, drug junkie, cult follower: the co-founder of the band Fleetwood Mac, Peter Green, is dead.
He died peacefully in his sleep at the age of 73, family members announced in an official statement on Saturday, and a further statement would be announced for the next few days.
Top musicians such as Peter Frampton praised Green as one of the best blues and rock guitarists.
In an emotional reaction, Mick Fleetwood spoke of a "monumental loss" for all former and current members of the band Fleetwood Mac.
Drummer Fleetwood and guitarist Green founded the now legendary band in London in 1967, and his dreamy instrumental hit "Albatross" remains unforgotten to this day.
The life of the musician ("The End Of The Game," "In The Skies") resembled a rollercoaster ride.
Green experienced a rapid rise with Fleetwood Mac - but the band celebrated their greatest successes without him.
There is said to have been a dispute, among other things, because Green wanted to donate all profits of the group to charity.
He began to perform in wide robes and with a large crucifix.
Mental problems are also said to have played a role.
Just three years after its formation, Green left the band in 1970.
A social decline followed.
The blues rock guitarist suffered from drug abuse and schizophrenia, as biographers reported.
Green was treated in psychiatry for a long time.
For much of the 1970s, the musician disappeared from the scene.
He is said to have lived temporarily on the street, worked as a cemetery gardener and spent time in an Israeli kibbutz.
Green was born in 1946 to a working-class Jewish family in Bethnal Green, London.
At a young age he was enthusiastic about US blues musicians such as B.B. king and Muddy Waters.
At the age of eleven he learned his first guitar chords.
The teenager began playing guitar professionally at the age of 15 and five years later got the chance to perform on stage as lead guitarist for the instrumental band Peter B's Looners.
Shortly afterwards, he was hired as a replacement for his idol Eric Clapton at the Bluesbreakers.
In the middle of the blues boom, Green founded Fleetwood Mac in the summer of 1967 together with his Bluesbreakers colleagues Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
The song "Albatross" composed by Green gave the group their first number 1 hit in the winter of 1968/69 and catapulted them to the top of the British music scene.
The rapid rise soon showed its downsides: Green could not cope with the media hype, his experiments with the drug LSD became more and more extreme.
He later commented on life between music and addiction in an interview: "The worst thing that has happened to me in life is the drugs - the best thing was to land a number 1 hit".
Towards the end of the decade, Green surprisingly achieved a respectable success in 1979 with an album inspired by religious themes.
Meanwhile Fleetwood Mac swam without him in a new formation on a wave of success.
Her 1977 album "Rumours" sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite various small solo successes, Green did not make a major comeback until he started again in 1996 with a group of fellow musicians.
The British Daily Telegraph spoke of a rock star who had returned to Earth.
Free of drugs, Green released several albums with the Peter Green Splinter Group until the band disbanded in 2004.
For music experts, he was already a blues legend during his lifetime - and with his soft sound one of the most influential guitarists of the past decades.
